Congolese nationals have been expressing their dissatisfaction with President Joseph Kabila's refusal to step down. PRETORIA - There is a strong security force presence in Kinshasa, the capital of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) after repeated clashes with protesters. At least 26 people have been killed in confrontations in the country.Congolese nationals have been expressing their dissatisfaction with President Joseph Kabila's refusal to step down.In South Africa, government has expressed concern over the situation in the DRC following protests in Pretoria on Tuesday, which resulted in nine arrests.Opposition leader Etienne Tshisekedi called on the Congolese people to peacefully resist Kabila, who has remained in power beyond his constitutional mandate with no election to pick a successor.Gunfire crackled in several districts of the capital, Kinshasa, a city of 12 million, as measures to thwart dissent raised fears of bloody repression.With a ban on demonstrations in force and a heavy military presence, Kinshasa's normally busy main boulevards were mostly deserted as pockets of youths gathered in side streets only to be dispersed by volleys of teargas.By sunset, the city was calm, although littered with debris from earlier rioting. Youths played soccer in the streets.In Lubumbashi, in the heart of Africa's richest copper- mining area, police and Kabila's elite Republican Guard fired live bullets to prevent demonstrations, said Gregoire Mulamba, a local human rights activist.Local activist Jean-Pierre Muteba reported at least one death, a 14-year-old boy shot by police. A police spokesman said he did not have enough information to comment.In the city of Kananga, in central Congo, fighting between security forces and a local clan militia shut down the airport.Kabila, who has ruled since his father, Laurent Kabila, was assassinated in 2001, rarely speaks about the issue in public, but his allies say the election was delayed because of logistical and financial problems. The constitutional court has ruled Kabila can stay on until the vote takes place.Additional reporting by Reuters.(Edited by Shimoney Regter)